# ðŸŒŸ Exercise 6 : A & B
# Instructions
# Create two variables, a and b.
# Each variable value should be a number.
# If a is bigger then b, have your code print Hello World.

a,b = 40,12
print({True: "Hello World", False: "dlorW olleH"} [a > b]) 


# Exercise 7 : Odd Or Even
# Instructions
# Write code that asks the user for a number and determines whether this number is odd or even.
number = int(input("Input a number"))
print({True: f"{number} is even", False: f"{number} is odd"} [number % 2 ==0]) 



# ðŸŒŸ Exercise 8 : Whatâ€™s Your Name ?
# Instructions
# Write code that asks the user for their name and determines whether or not you have the same name, print out a funny message based on the outcome.
storeName = "maman"
userName = str(input("Input your name").lower())
print({True: f"You has same name{storeName} as the CEO", False: f"Hello Welcome {userName}"} [storeName == userName]) 



# ðŸŒŸ Exercise 9 : Tall Enough To Ride A Roller Coaster
# Instructions
# Write code that will ask the user for their height in inches.
# If they are over 145cm print a message that states they are tall enough to ride.
# If they are not tall enough print a message that says they need to grow some more to ride.

height = float(input("Input height in inches:"))
convertHeight = height * 2.54
print({True: "You are tall enough to ride", False: "Grow some more to ride"} [convertHeight > 154]) 






